    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my civil eng midterm and im a bit stuck on materials. why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside concrete foundations? like i get that concrete is strong, but why does the steel part matter so much for the actual structure? i'm specifically confused about the difference between compressive and tensile strength in this context.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Steel rebar is crucial in concrete foundations because concrete is incredibly strong under compression, but it is very weak when being pulled apart, which is called tension.  The steel, being much stronger in tension, is placed strategically to handle those pulling forces that concrete cannot manage alone. Think of it like this: concrete handles the squishing, while the rebar handles the stretching, making the whole system robust enough to withstand real-world loads. This combination creates a composite material far superior to either component used in isolation.",
      "source": "target",
