    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if concrete is basically just good at squishing, what kind of forces are actually trying to stretch or pull the foundation apart? like, is it just the weight of the building, or is there something else happening inside the slab that makes tension a problem?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The weight of the building is a primary source of compression, but tension forces arise from various stresses, not just the static load. When a foundation slab bends—which happens under uneven loads or due to soil settlement—the underside of the slab experiences tension as it tries to curve downwards. Furthermore, lateral forces, like wind or minor seismic activity, can induce bending or shear stresses that pull on the concrete. These tensile stresses are what the rebar is specifically there to counteract.",
      "source": "target",
